00:04:26.720 --> 00:04:29.980
The first of course centered
around this individual.

00:04:29.980 --> 00:04:33.390
What you see here is Juan
Ponce de Leon's signature.

00:04:33.390 --> 00:04:39.130
And in Florida in 2013 commemorated
the 500 year anniversary

00:04:39.130 --> 00:04:42.570
of something related related
to Juan Ponce de Leon.

00:04:42.570 --> 00:04:45.650
It was still quite a
mystery as the year unfolded,

00:04:45.650 --> 00:04:49.910
what is it that we're commemorating
and what exactly did he do

00:04:49.910 --> 00:04:51.860
and why are we commemorating this?

00:04:51.860 --> 00:04:54.080
And often the answer especially

00:04:54.080 --> 00:04:56.930
in the political sphere
was well we need

00:04:56.930 --> 00:04:59.530
to tell everybody that we're old.

00:04:59.530 --> 00:05:01.540
That we're first.

00:05:01.540 --> 00:05:05.050
They love first's and oldest
even when first aren't first's

00:05:05.050 --> 00:05:06.650
and oldest are not oldest.

00:05:06.650 --> 00:05:08.880
And so there was this
whole discussion.

00:05:08.880 --> 00:05:10.540
I don't know if you
followed the debate,

00:05:10.540 --> 00:05:13.440
sometimes a rather heated
debate that unfolded in Florida

00:05:13.440 --> 00:05:16.480
over where did Ponce land?

00:05:16.480 --> 00:05:18.070
And different communities fought.

00:05:18.070 --> 00:05:20.600
There were newspaper articles,
battles back and forth

00:05:20.600 --> 00:05:22.170
about where Ponce landed.

00:05:22.170 --> 00:05:23.730
So I guess the real takeaway

00:05:23.730 --> 00:05:28.240
in 2013 was no one
agreed where Ponce landed.

00:05:28.240 --> 00:05:32.430
And he did something, we're old.

00:05:32.430 --> 00:05:37.430
So that was the takeaway I suppose.

00:05:37.430 --> 00:05:38.730
Two years later the City

00:05:38.730 --> 00:05:43.090
of St. Augustine commemorated
its 450 year anniversary.

00:05:43.090 --> 00:05:46.750
And of course you have
to have cake I guess

00:05:46.750 --> 00:05:49.500
when you're celebrating
historical anniversaries.

00:05:49.500 --> 00:05:54.210
This is the day of the
anniversary, September 8, 2015,

00:05:54.210 --> 00:05:56.390
marked the 450 year commemoration.

00:05:56.390 --> 00:05:59.200
What was striking about that
in a way when I reflect back

00:05:59.200 --> 00:06:04.380
on that moment, the highest
ranking political official

00:06:04.380 --> 00:06:07.320 position:56%
to attend the 450th, the actual day,

00:06:07.320 --> 00:06:10.830
the 450th was Florida's
Secretary of State.

00:06:10.830 --> 00:06:18.630
So it still didn't I guess generate
a kind of national interest.

00:06:18.630 --> 00:06:22.460
Now of course ten days later the
Royal Majesties of Spain arrived,

00:06:22.460 --> 00:06:25.090
King Felipe VI and Queen Letizia.

00:06:25.090 --> 00:06:28.730
And then lots of people came
to St. Augustine ten days

00:06:28.730 --> 00:06:31.260
after the actual anniversary.

00:06:31.260 --> 00:06:33.940
He's, this is King Felipe VI.

00:06:33.940 --> 00:06:35.930
He's 6'6".

00:06:35.930 --> 00:06:40.260
I'm getting there I
hope one day to be 6'6".

00:06:40.260 --> 00:06:44.040
I'm standing behind him so
it makes me look shorter.

00:06:44.040 --> 00:06:47.210
In any case they came and of course

00:06:47.210 --> 00:06:48.930
that attracted a great
deal of interest.

00:06:48.930 --> 00:06:52.600
And I remember speaking with the
city manager during that visit

00:06:52.600 --> 00:06:57.480
and shortly thereafter and he
really posed this question.

00:06:57.480 --> 00:07:01.290
Now that the anniversaries
have passed,

00:07:01.290 --> 00:07:04.610
now that there's been national
and international attention.

00:07:04.610 --> 00:07:06.740
The Royal Majesties
of Spain have come

00:07:06.740 --> 00:07:10.540
to commemorate this
moment, where do we go?

00:07:10.540 --> 00:07:12.030
What's next?

00:07:12.030 --> 00:07:14.950
And sometimes it was a
little disheartening.

00:07:14.950 --> 00:07:19.470
I remember reviewing a national
history textbook not long ago.

00:07:19.470 --> 00:07:21.060
I won't mention the state.

00:07:21.060 --> 00:07:24.220
It begins with M and
ends with chusetts.

00:07:24.220 --> 00:07:28.890
But it was a national
history text that was going

00:07:28.890 --> 00:07:31.580
out to junior high school
students around the country.

00:07:31.580 --> 00:07:36.830
And one of the chapters was on
the colonization of North America.

00:07:36.830 --> 00:07:40.330
And the chapter began
with Jamestown.

00:07:40.330 --> 00:07:45.400
And I thought what
are we doing wrong?

00:07:45.400 --> 00:07:47.830
The first people of African descent

00:07:47.830 --> 00:07:52.340
in the textbook came
to Virginia in 1619.

00:07:52.340 --> 00:07:57.840
So that's only off by 106 years
of the first recorded person

00:07:57.840 --> 00:08:00.860
of African descent, Juan
Garrido who was part

00:08:00.860 --> 00:08:03.300
of Ponce de Leon's 1513 expedition.

00:08:03.300 --> 00:08:07.310
So maybe there's something we
can do a little bit differently.

00:08:07.310 --> 00:08:10.380
And what we've, what we're
starting and what we'll launch

00:08:10.380 --> 00:08:15.660 position:56%
in the fall is a center, digital
center for colonial Florida history.

00:08:15.660 --> 00:08:17.640
And it's really built on projects.

00:08:17.640 --> 00:08:23.760
A whole series of projects that
preceded this one, that are working

00:08:23.760 --> 00:08:25.460
at the same time as this one.

00:08:25.460 --> 00:08:28.360 position:56%
Of course the Spanish website Pares,

00:08:28.360 --> 00:08:30.350
if you're not familiar
with this site.

00:08:30.350 --> 00:08:34.820
It's an absolutely remarkable
website of documents and maps

00:08:34.820 --> 00:08:40.920
from a number of almost a dozen
Spanish state archives, digitized.

00:08:40.920 --> 00:08:44.190
There are millions of
documents, maps, images,

00:08:44.190 --> 00:08:46.980
photographs from the
Spanish civil war,

00:08:46.980 --> 00:08:53.060
documents from medieval Spain all
the way up to the 20th century.

00:08:53.060 --> 00:08:56.730
And this is something that the
Spanish government's been doing

00:08:56.730 --> 00:08:58.540
since the 1980s.

00:08:58.540 --> 00:09:01.630
They were really a pioneer
in terms of digitization,

00:09:01.630 --> 00:09:03.310
making this material available.

00:09:03.310 --> 00:09:06.820
It's not the most user
friendly website.

00:09:06.820 --> 00:09:08.370
Maybe that was a compromise.

00:09:08.370 --> 00:09:12.170
We'll make the documents
available but it'll be so difficult

00:09:12.170 --> 00:09:15.100
to navigate that nobody
will find the documents.

00:09:15.100 --> 00:09:16.800
And it's pretty close.

00:09:16.800 --> 00:09:21.380
It's a challenging one if you
have not used Pares in the past.

00:09:21.380 --> 00:09:23.550
But of course it has
some remarkable,

00:09:23.550 --> 00:09:26.450
remarkable documents in it.

00:09:26.450 --> 00:09:31.180
Just some examples of some
the characters who lived

00:09:31.180 --> 00:09:36.990
in colonial Florida who, about whom
you can research through Pares,

00:09:36.990 --> 00:09:41.020
this is a letter written
to King Philip III.

00:09:41.020 --> 00:09:45.330
It dates to the 20th
of February of 1600.

00:09:45.330 --> 00:09:53.000
And it was written by this woman,
Dona Maria who was a Cacica,

00:09:53.000 --> 00:09:55.940
Native American, a
Timucua Indian Chief.

00:09:55.940 --> 00:10:00.050
One of numerous letters that Dona
Maria wrote to the King of Spain.

00:10:00.050 --> 00:10:02.700
And there were responses.

00:10:02.700 --> 00:10:04.680
She is a figure that outside

00:10:04.680 --> 00:10:08.340
of St. Augustine is not
particularly well known.

00:10:08.340 --> 00:10:13.270
My guess is if this letter were
signed Pocahontas the letter would

00:10:13.270 --> 00:10:15.590
probably be in every textbook,

00:10:15.590 --> 00:10:18.350
fourth grade textbook
in the country.

00:10:18.350 --> 00:10:20.840
And yet we know quite
a bit about her.

00:10:20.840 --> 00:10:26.350
Documents like a very small trove
of final wills and testaments.

00:10:26.350 --> 00:10:29.020
We, it's rare to find
final wills from Florida.

00:10:29.020 --> 00:10:33.280
There are only that we've been
able to locate, only about 40.

00:10:33.280 --> 00:10:37.760
And there are reasons for that
that I'm happy to discuss later.

00:10:37.760 --> 00:10:42.310
But the oldest one that we've
uncovered is a will from 1566,

00:10:42.310 --> 00:10:46.680
one year after St. Augustine
was established in 1565.

00:10:46.680 --> 00:10:47.980
Is that better?

00:10:47.980 --> 00:10:49.420
There, okay, sorry.

00:10:49.420 --> 00:10:54.280
And it's a will from a young
man named Bernard Jansen

00:10:54.280 --> 00:10:56.680
who was from Bremen, Germany.

00:10:56.680 --> 00:11:00.790
And poor, couldn't sign his name.

00:11:00.790 --> 00:11:05.570
But it's a handful of wills
that will part of this center.

00:11:05.570 --> 00:11:09.580
When we finish we'll publish all
of these wills with transcriptions

00:11:09.580 --> 00:11:12.500
and translations of these
final wills from Florida.

00:11:12.500 --> 00:11:14.920
And tales of people
like this individual,

00:11:14.920 --> 00:11:18.870
whose real name was actually
Darby Glavin, he's Irish.

00:11:18.870 --> 00:11:22.830
And the Spanish had no
patience with Darby as a name

00:11:22.830 --> 00:11:25.680
so they just called
him David Glavid.

00:11:25.680 --> 00:11:29.260
And David Glavid was,
has a fascinating story.

00:11:29.260 --> 00:11:32.880
I mean, know about him in
the English historiography

00:11:32.880 --> 00:11:36.330
that he was one of
the Roanoke settlers,

00:11:36.330 --> 00:11:38.910
that Francis Drake took
him back to England.

00:11:38.910 --> 00:11:40.210
He was sent back.

00:11:40.210 --> 00:11:44.310
And somehow was captured by
the Spanish and was sentenced

00:11:44.310 --> 00:11:46.060
to a life in the galleys.

00:11:46.060 --> 00:11:48.350
That's the English
version of the narrative.

00:11:48.350 --> 00:11:51.550
The Spanish story is
completely different.

00:11:51.550 --> 00:11:54.900
David Glavid ends up
living in St. Augustine.

00:11:54.900 --> 00:11:58.840
He testifies that he was a
fisherman off the coast of Ireland.

00:11:58.840 --> 00:12:01.980
And the English kidnapped him.

00:12:01.980 --> 00:12:05.500
Took him to Roanoke against
his will, stole his boat.

00:12:05.500 --> 00:12:09.880
And he ended up at Roanoke,
went back to England with Drake.

00:12:09.880 --> 00:12:12.610
And then Queen Elizabeth
II sent him back.

00:12:12.610 --> 00:12:15.660
When he arrived in
Puerto Rico he ran away.

00:12:15.660 --> 00:12:19.280
And he later joined the
Spanish, lived in St. Augustine.

00:12:19.280 --> 00:12:22.000
He was a merchant and a
soldier in St. Augustine.

00:12:22.000 --> 00:12:24.590
He was the guy you would
go to to get stuff.

00:12:24.590 --> 00:12:27.950
If you wanted textiles
from Asia, you wanted some.

00:12:27.950 --> 00:12:33.180
David Glavid was the merchant
who could acquire those goods.

00:12:33.180 --> 00:12:35.840
Or somebody like Luisa Menendez.

00:12:35.840 --> 00:12:38.920
We know lots of stories like
this from Mexico and Peru.

00:12:38.920 --> 00:12:41.830
As a young girl she was
taken captive by the Spanish.

00:12:41.830 --> 00:12:46.390
She was probably at the time
between the age of eight and ten.

00:12:46.390 --> 00:12:48.850
She ended up living in
a Spanish settlement

00:12:48.850 --> 00:12:50.390
in Florida called Santa Elena.

00:12:50.390 --> 00:12:53.900
We call today Paris
Island, South Carolina.

00:12:53.900 --> 00:12:58.490
And she was a domestic servant
in the home of St. Augustine,

00:12:58.490 --> 00:13:03.500
St. Augustine's founder's
wife, Dona Maria de Solis.

00:13:03.500 --> 00:13:07.740
She then ends up marrying a Spanish
solider whose 20 years her senior.

00:13:07.740 --> 00:13:11.350
And she lives certainly from
what we can document well

00:13:11.350 --> 00:13:13.720
into the early 17th century.

00:13:13.720 --> 00:13:16.920
Of course the AGI then contains
all kinds of information

00:13:16.920 --> 00:13:22.610
about food stuffs and supplies that
went from Spain to Florida or Cuba

00:13:22.610 --> 00:13:25.380
to Florida, other places
with those supplies.

00:13:25.380 --> 00:13:28.870
This is simply an inventory of
food stuffs that went to Florida

00:13:28.870 --> 00:13:33.370
with the Menendez 1565 expedition.

00:13:33.370 --> 00:13:35.610
So there's all this
material available.

00:13:35.610 --> 00:13:39.990
It's not material you would
really publish by themselves.

00:13:39.990 --> 00:13:41.850
And what I'm going to frame

00:13:41.850 --> 00:13:45.650
for you is the idea we have
for this digital center.

00:13:45.650 --> 00:13:50.160
For us it really began with a
project that I did with a couple

00:13:50.160 --> 00:13:54.160 position:56%
of graduate students at the
University of North Florida and then

00:13:54.160 --> 00:13:58.310
at the University of South Florida
to digitize the parish records

00:13:58.310 --> 00:14:00.050
in St. Augustine, Florida.

00:14:00.050 --> 00:14:03.520 position:56%
And these records date back to 1594.

00:14:03.520 --> 00:14:06.260
They're the some of
the oldest documents

00:14:06.260 --> 00:14:09.550
in the United States
about the United States.

00:14:09.550 --> 00:14:13.730
And they're parish
records, baptisms, deaths,

00:14:13.730 --> 00:14:16.300
confirmations, marriages.

00:14:16.300 --> 00:14:21.410
And we started a project
to digitize 6,000 pages

00:14:21.410 --> 00:14:23.630
of the colonial parish records.

00:14:23.630 --> 00:14:25.320
And this was the team.

00:14:25.320 --> 00:14:29.930
We did it for, I think our
budget was something like $5,500.

00:14:29.930 --> 00:14:33.200
And we digitized all
of these documents

00:14:33.200 --> 00:14:35.170
which are now available online.

00:14:35.170 --> 00:14:37.900
You can see on the left
that's Jane Landers

00:14:37.900 --> 00:14:40.580
from Vanderbilt University
who's written extensively

00:14:40.580 --> 00:14:43.160
about Africans in Florida.

00:14:43.160 --> 00:14:46.230
And then my two graduate
students on the far right

00:14:46.230 --> 00:14:49.370
and Jane's team in between.

00:14:49.370 --> 00:14:51.950
And this is what some of
these records look like.

00:14:51.950 --> 00:14:56.460
This is one of the early
marriage records from 1594.

00:14:56.460 --> 00:14:59.010
We do have the first
recorded baptism

00:14:59.010 --> 00:15:01.870
of anybody of African descent.

00:15:01.870 --> 00:15:04.790
