00:58:16.600 --> 00:58:22.820
Now this is, it's hard to fathom.

00:58:22.820 --> 00:58:26.370
How many people really have
crossed the Atlantic 50 times

00:58:26.370 --> 00:58:27.780
in an airplane?

00:58:27.780 --> 00:58:31.720
Let alone in 16th century ships.

00:58:31.720 --> 00:58:34.530
He once sailed from St.
Augustine to the Canary Islands

00:58:34.530 --> 00:58:40.010
in a small chalupa and
made that trip in 18 days.

00:58:40.010 --> 00:58:42.910
So if we could plot them over time

00:58:42.910 --> 00:58:45.380
and Francisco's team
would do a timeline,

00:58:45.380 --> 00:58:48.680
you could plot an individual's
life and that movement.

00:58:48.680 --> 00:58:52.320
And that's one of the things that
we want to incorporate into this.

00:58:52.320 --> 00:58:57.460 position:56%
Because I think anybody who works on
Colonial Latin American history one

00:58:57.460 --> 00:59:03.750
of the first things that is so
striking is how much people moved.

00:59:03.750 --> 00:59:07.330
People who were in Italy, in
Flanders, in different parts

00:59:07.330 --> 00:59:11.620
of Spain, in New Spain, in
Peru, Northern South America

00:59:11.620 --> 00:59:15.910
and had networks of people in
the movement of that information.

00:59:15.910 --> 00:59:19.060
And lots of people have
written about this.

00:59:19.060 --> 00:59:23.930
We'd like to try to find ways
to visualize that movement

00:59:23.930 --> 00:59:26.570
so that it becomes very clear
to those who look at it.

00:59:26.570 --> 00:59:30.230
And say wow, I didn't realize
there was this kind of movement.

00:59:30.230 --> 00:59:34.230
And plot Menendez's
movement over his life.

00:59:34.230 --> 00:59:36.030
So.

